comment.narrative:
The target has been reached on a continuous annual basis (83 %). 

Just like in the previous review, the CPP National Coordination has initiated, facilitated and /or organized consultations within the relevant frameworks (such as workshops, working sessions or meetings of the consultation frameworks, print-audio-visual media) to: 


(i) Share and disseminate the knowledge generated in the area of Sustainable Land Management;


(ii) Seek consensus on policy and regulatory responses related to sustainable management, wetlands, pastoral zones and environmental education;


(iii) Lay the foundation for the implementation of the Strategic Investment Framework for Sustainable Land Management through the preparation of project sheets for fund raising in view of the gradual expansion of the geographic coverage of SLM interventions countrywide.


Similarly, the CPP National Coordination Sub-Program has organized two sessions of its Steering Committee on adaptive management and implementation of the CPP Program. These sessions were attended by their statutory members including among others the representatives of the Steering Committees of CPP Regional Sub-Programs. 

Each of the two CPP Regional Programs has also organized two annual sessions of their respective Steering Committees for adaptive management and implementation of their Sub-Program.


The first phase of the CPP/IFAD Sub-Program having ended in December 2013, It should be noted that the CPP Program now has three Sub-Programs financed by GEF instead of four, including the current one as follows:


1) UNDP-GEF "National Subprogram for Coordination and Institutional Development on Sustainable Land Management" (this project, ongoing since early 2010);


3) UNDP-GEF "CPP Sub-Program for SLM in Boucle du Mouhoun Region" (ongoing since 2011 with project manager in place);


4) UNDP-GEF "CPP Subprogram for SLM in the Centre-West Region " (ongoing since November 2013 with project manager in place).

The target has been achieved since the previous review (100 %).

In fact, just like in the previous review, the project has pursued the replication of the 55 SLM best practices through : 


(i) The reproduction and dissemination of 1300 copies of the French versions and 4 local languages versions of the document on the capitalization on these 55 best practices on sustainable land management;  


(ii) The dissemination of the various soft versions of the document on the capitalization on best SLM practices on the website (www.onedd-burkina.info). This website got at least 33.974 visitors during the period under review;


(iii) The dissemination through the website (www.onedd-burkina.info) of methodological guides on pastoral development schemes, wetlands policy, national environmental legislations and policies as well as international environmental conventions and agreements;


(iv) The validation of methodological guides to the development of pastoral zone specifications as well as the guide on sustainable wetland management.


Moreover, the implementation of the Sustainable Land Management communication action plan has made it possible to strengthen the replication of the best practices in sustainable land management through:


-	Publication and broadcast of articles on best practices in the print -audio-visual press such as the bulletin « Notre Environnement » of the National Council for Environment and Sustainable Development, radio stations and national TV stations;


-	Production of the documentary film on SLM best practices;



-	Participation in exhibitions in the sidelines of national fora such as the National Farmers’ Day.

The target of establishing has been reached during the previous review, sustainability and functioning were pursued through:


(i) Co-financing by several national partners of NOESD following our advocacy;


(ii) Adoption of a mechanism for the collection, sharing, quality control and validation of the Observatory data and information produced; 


(iii) Launching of the equipment provision process to some NOESD partners and updating of its data base;


(iv) Facilitation National and international stakeholders’ access to NOESD information through feeding data into its website: www.onedd-burkina.info (more than 33.974 visitors during the period under review).

The target is reached at about 75%. Supplementary progress towards this target was registered during the period under review through:


(i) the inclusion of the setting up regional platforms of East, Sahel, Center-north and South –west in the Forest Investment Program and Great Green Wall for the Sahara and Sahel Initiative, which are being implemented since January 2015,  as well as the strengthening of regional platforms of Boucle du Mouhoun and Centre-west;


(ii) developing the skills of the regional platforms of Mouhoun and center-west in alternative management of land tenure-related conflicts, sustainable land management concept and project and program formulation;


(iii) Le recrutement d'une maitrise d'ouvrage délégué (ACOMOD Burkina) pour la réalisation de la construction du siège du CPP devant accueillir entre autres les locaux de la Plateforme Nationale de Partenariat pour la Gestion Durable des Terres;


(iv) Launching of the required resource mobilization process notably for the functioning of the National sustainable land management Platform which was translated into the validation of the Strategic Investment Framework for Sustainable Land Management.

The achievement of this target (100%) during the previous review was consolidated during the current review by:


(i)	The validation of the wetlands development and sustainable management guide;


(ii)	Validation of a methodological guide on the preparation of pastoral zone terms of reference; 


(iii)	Reproduction and dissemination of 870 copies of the methodological guide on pastoral zone development and security;


