(viii)	Sharing of the experiences of the National Partnership Program for Sustainable Land Management with other countries, particularly Sub-Saharan countries and countries parties to the CoP of the Framework Convention on Climate Change:


o	The ONEDD website  (www.onedd-burkina.info) ;

o	Attendance to fora organized by the TerrAfrica Initiative and the Secretariat of the Convention on Climate Change.

The target was fully reached (100%) in view of the achievements in previous reviews. 


The current review has revealed the following progress:


(i) At least 120 specialists including 30 women were trained in the thirteen regions (or about 9 specialists per region including 2 women) on the themes on « Concepts and Principles of  and Approaches to Sustainable Land Management», «Formulation of sustainable land management projects at the communal or regional levels», and « Alternative management of land tenure –related conflicts». The idea was to provide advisory support to communal and regional councils as well as other stakeholders;


(ii) 112 resource persons of central structures trained on the themes on « Concepts and Principles of  and Approaches to Sustainable Land Management», «Formulation of sustainable land management projects at the communal or regional levels», and « Alternative management of land tenure –related conflicts» and «preparation of climate change adaptation projects». They will in turn contribute to providing the regions with skilled specialists in these fields of knowledge. In addition all these trained specialists were given sustainable land management best practice tools  produced by the CPP National Coordination Sub-Program;


(iii) Preparation of the report on the pre-test of three draft teacher’s guides on mainstreaming Sustainable Land Management (SLM) Best Practices in primary school curricula.

